<p>Today, I noticed the crisscrossing lines where the skin by your mouth meets your cheeks. Your eyes bend downwards. I want to scrub those lines off softly, with the tips of my thumbs. </p><p>You dreamt bright, warm spaces for me, so large that I squint when I look from end to end. You dreamt me into grand, empty landscapes </p><p>no man could fill. You did not ask me to – </p><p>Just to expand in their space. Just to stand in their light, so, naked, I could feel the heat from the sun you’d laid there. </p><p>Today, I remembered that you will not live forever. That those lines along the corners of your mouth cut far deeper than they appear. That they sever skin from bone at the end of life, and the red light from the fading sun carves them even deeper. </p><p>I want to scrub them off softly, with the tips of my thumbs. </p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /> </p>
